[normal]2.7
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Over £200m was awarded through the 
[normal]Young People’s Fund[bold] [bold](YPF)[bold] supporting projects across the UK t
[normal]hat provide activities for disadvantaged or vulnerable young people, including young people who are losing touch with the education system. Arrangements and approaches for the programmes varied, but all highlighted the importance of actively involving youn
[normal]g people in planning and running projects that set out to – among other aims – improve young people’s confidence, well-being and engagement in the economy and wider society. Across the UK, about 700,000 young people took part in YPF projects.
[normal] 
[normal]Young people 
[normal]served on awa
[normal]rd-making panels for grants to national organisations,
[normal] local organisations
[normal] and
[normal] individuals. 
[normal]([bold]Question 6[bold])[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]2.8
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Projects have also helped to develop young people’s employability skills, including presentation and communication skills, leadership, and assertiveness. For instance 3,356 young people aged 11 to 25 received awards of £250 to £5,000 to run their own proje
[normal]ct as part of Big Boost. Many of them benefited from training and developed skills for their future careers including team working, communication and decision making. In Scotland YPF consistently helped between 6% and 16% of young people to access employme
[normal]nt, go to college, access an apprenticeship or training or to go to university. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.9
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A range of YPF programme evaluation reports have captured learning and informed our current and future investments in this area. As well as considering the overall success of
[normal] projects and programmes in achieving what they set out to, the evaluation had a strong focus on considering approaches to effective involvement by young people – so the publications available here include good practice guides on that and related subjects
[normal] 
[normal]([bold]Question 6[bold])[bold]. The reports can be found here: 
[normal]http://www.biglotteryfund.org.uk/research/children-and-young-people/evaluating-the-young-peoples
[normal]-fund
[normal]. 
